    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## Radius of Convergence [S+N]\n\nNot all Taylor series converge everywhere. The function\n$f(x) = \\frac{1}{1+x^2}$ is analytic on all of $\\mathbb{R}$, yet its\nTaylor series around $x=0$ has **radius of convergence** $R = 1$.\n\nThis happens because $f$ has poles at $x = \\pm i$ in the complex plane,\nand the radius of convergence equals the distance to the nearest\nsingularity. Maxima derives the series symbolically; the plot reveals\nthe divergence outside $|x| < 1$.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "/* Taylor expansion of 1/(1+x^2) — converges only for |x| < 1 */\ng : 1/(1 + x^2)$\nT10 : ratdisrep(taylor(g, x, 0, 10))$\nT20 : ratdisrep(taylor(g, x, 0, 20))$\n\nprint(\"T_10 =\", T10)$\nprint(\"T_20 =\", T20)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 92,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "T_10 = -x^10+x^8-x^6+x^4-x^2+1\nT_20 = x^20-x^18+x^16-x^14+x^12-x^10+x^8-x^6+x^4-x^2+1"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "/* Plot: the Taylor series diverges wildly outside |x| < 1 */\nax_draw2d(\n  color=black, line_width=3, name=\"1/(1+x^2)\",\n  explicit(g, x, -2, 2),\n  color=red, name=\"Taylor order 10\",\n  explicit(T10, x, -2, 2),\n  color=blue, name=\"Taylor order 20\",\n  explicit(T20, x, -2, 2),\n  title=\"Radius of Convergence: 1/(1+x^2)\",\n  yrange=[-2, 3], grid=true\n)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 93,
      "outputs": [
